{"id": "50550", 
"title": "Bug 50550 - PropFind 404 error after MkCol success", 
"description": "Bug 50550 - PropFind 404 error after MkCol success. This suggests that this issue may be related to caching. Note: This situation appears similar to call 21288 (FIXED - 'DirContext caching problem with Dreamweaver 6 when recursively creating directories'). Reproducible using a Jackrabbit client:

HttpClient client = new HttpClient();
String newDir = 'http://localhost:8080/webdav/output/' + UUID.randomUUID() + '/';
// Comment out this request to make second PropFind successful
HttpMethod propFindMethod1 = new PropFindMethod(newDir);
client.executeMethod(propFindMethod1);
propFindMethod1.releaseConnection();
HttpMethod mkcolMethod = new MkColMethod(newDir);
client.executeMethod(mkcolMethod);
mkcolMethod.releaseConnection();
HttpMethod propFindMethod = new PropFindMethod(newDir);
client.executeMethod(propFindMethod);
propFindMethod.releaseConnection();", 
"OB": "When executing a PropFind call on a resource after a MkCol call for the same resource, a 404 error is returned.", 
"EB": "The PropFind call after a MkCol call should not result in a 404 error. The resource should be successfully found.", 
"SR": "To reproduce the issue, follow these steps:
1. Create a Jackrabbit client using HttpClient.
2. Generate a new directory URL by appending a random UUID to 'http://localhost:8080/webdav/output/'.
3. Comment out the first PropFind request (propFindMethod1) to make the second PropFind request successful.
4. Execute the MkCol method using the new directory URL.
5. Release the connection for the MkCol method.
6. Execute the PropFind method using the same directory URL.
7. Release the connection for the PropFind method.
8. Observe that a 404 error is returned instead of successfully finding the resource."}
